Yes, I leave metal utensils in the microwave! Metals causing sparks doesn’t always happen, and most of the time, in my experience, a spoon or fork won’t do it. But it might, so if you’re going to try, watch it before walking away. 

If you want more details on why/how look up a great YouTube video from @mehdi_sadaghdar (ElectroBOOM on YouTube) for the explanation 😄.

EDIT: Some people think this is something I shouldn’t tell others, but I’m not in favour of dumbing down the information to “you can’t put metal in the microwave” because that’s not true, and we’re not children. Many people can benefit from learning about this. I did not say sparks never happen, and I’ve given the precautions if you want to try it out.

The best Indian food in Vancouver can be found in the most unlikely of places, at a university diner…cooked by…a Chinese couple? Yes! This is @onlyucafeubc, which was also my first restaurant job in Canada, and this family became a home away from home for me. The two young girls are their daughters who were just little kids when I worked here 🥺❤️.

Only U Cafe looks like a typical greasy spoon diner, but the owners are Chinese Indians, and while they started out with your typical fare of bacon and eggs, they eventually went back to their roots and started serving excellent Indian food in addition to the also-fantastic breakfast. 

I went back to visit them after too many years, and had two excellent dishes that are Indian street food, which is not easy to find elsewhere in this city.

Sometimes the best food is in the most surprising places 🥰.

Anyone else hate having to buy a whole head of celery? I usually need a couple stalks of celery, max, but only some stores sell them lose. So sometimes I have to buy the whole thing…and what do you do with the rest of it?

So I made a celery stir fry, and the sauce was actually just some leftover kao mun gai (Hainanese chicken rice) dipping sauce. I knew that the soybean paste in the sauce goes well with celery so decided to give it a go. Turned out great as a veg side dish!

How do you use celery? And no, I do not enjoy snacking on them raw 🤣.

Some people have asked me how some Thai families manage to cook a multi-dish dinner every single day. (In my house growing up we always had 3-4 dishes). 

The answer is that most of the dishes are very simple. There might be one complex dish, but the rest is very quick. We also don’t take extra steps to maximize flavour and all that cheffy stuff I often share with you. It’s a lot of dump-and-stir 😂.

Also, it’s not every family. Many busy people just cook 1-2 things, or more commonly, buy takeout every day cuz food is so cheap there. 

Anyone regularly cooks multi dish meals for dinner? I think it’s a very common Asian thing.

My brother @artchongart came to visit and when asked what he wanted for his last dinner here, he requested something that surprised me: Pad Mama.

Mama is Thai instant noodles and pad mama is, in my brother’s words, “the taste of childhood.” 

Mama noodles have a very particular taste and texture (i.e the best) and you can’t really substitute another kind of instant noodles and expect the same results. If you’ve had mama, you know what I mean.

Recipe is on my site, and while you’ve got Mama, make the salad too 😄.

In my upcoming book #SABAI (available for pre-order now at link in bio!) there’s a small section where I wrote a love letter to ground pork, one of my fave ingredients.

Ground pork is a staple Thai ingredient, and growing up I loved making it as it gave me an excuse to hold a cleaver and hack away at it without restraint. 😆 

As a busy person now, I love it even more because it’s quick to thaw, extremely versatile, easy to cook, totally forgiving…just the perfect protein really. 

This is Kua Gling. A southern Thai dish of ground pork stir fried with curry paste. I hacked this one using random bits of curry paste left in my fridge (a mix or red and yellow) and added some green beans and served with fresh celery leaves. 

Recipe for this is in my bio link, you can make the homemade paste for the “real” kua gling or just use whatever paste you already have and make a tasty dish anyway cuz who cares as long as it tastes good. 😎

Talk about a dish that surprised me…this one blew me away the first time I had it.

“Moo Manao” means “lime pork”. It’s a popular dish, but the description honestly did not excite me. Pork is marinated and simply blanched in hot water,  placed on a pile of cabbage, with a Thai salad dressing on top. To a Thai person it sounds like a basic salad….but with cabbage.

But it has become one of my favourite Thai dishes and def one of my top salad picks. Pork is marinated and “velveted”, so it’s tender and juicy. The garlicky, spicy, tart dressing is amazing on it, and the cabbage adds the crunch that completes it. 

Now I understand what the fuss was about.

If you buy new crop rice, and it’s not what you usually buy, it’s worth keeping a note to remind yourself. 

New crop rice is basically rice that was harvested this year, so it didn’t have time to dry out as long as old crop rice.

So the rice is more moist and therefore takes less water to cook. I like new crop rice cuz it is fluffier, softer and more fragrant. But you need to add a little bit less water to it.

PS. Sticky rice also comes in old or new crop. This one is actually sticky rice.

PSS. If it doesn’t say “new crop” assume it’s old crop.

🌈 Tip for making rainbow pancakes: dividing batter into small batches and adding food colouring to each means you need to stir the batter more than normal, which could toughen the pancakes due to excessive gluten development. Just booked my next flight home, so here’s a throw back to my last trip to Thailand. When people ask me where they should eat in Thailand, they’re hoping I’d give them hidden street food gems and such…but folks, what I ALWAYS look forward to in Thailand is the extravagant-over-the-top HOTEL BUFFET.

What you see here is BREAKFAST. Forget what you know about “hotel breakfast” in N America, this is next level. Yes, all this is ONE buffet. Yes, there is Indian food, noodle soup stall, and honey off the comb. 

This is at the Marriott in Hua Hin, but most major hotels in Bangkok have a similar thing. Though maybe not quite as big, this one was pretty epic. 

Yes it’s expensive, so this would be considered a treat, but I really think it’s a good deal and a great experience, especially compared to what I get for the same money in Vancouver. Aunty Pai loves me a good deal and I think this fits the bill.

✈️ BTW tix to Thailand are hella $$$$ right now, I just booked mine for September cuz that’s when prices are reasonable again.

When I was in Toronto I went to @yuseafoodyorkdale. It was the second restaurant I went to in TO where you order directly from a tablet without having to go through a server. So I assume it’s becoming more common there. 

Felt a little weird at first cuz it felt like I was online shopping lol, but I actually really like it. I can take as long as I need (no more “please give us a few more mins”) and more importantly your order gets to the kitchen instantly, no more waiting for anyone to come, so food came faster. Servers are still there to bring you the food and other things of course but the ordering part is definitely improved with technology.

Have you experienced this before? What do you think?

When you open the freezer and find out your husband is a traitor. 🤣

JUST KIDDING. He bought it because he thought it would be “good to know”. Well I usually like PC stuff but this thing turned out to be pretty bad. 

Perfect timing since I just shared a deep dive into rice noodles (see link in bio for the video). Rice noodles do not do well in the freezer, so no, you cannot freeze your leftover pad Thai or pad see ew and microwave it next week. 

Once cooked, rice noodles don’t even do well in the fridge. They will continue to absorb any liquid in the dish and swell, and when reheated they will over cook from that absorbed liquid. If the dish is quite dry, you can fridge it for a day and microwave and have edible results, but it won’t ever be as good. 

However, soaked, uncooked noodles can be kept in the fridge for several days so you can do that to save time. Just make sure they are drained very well, and that there is no pooling liquid in the container.

If you, like me, often find baked goods sold in stores too sweet and/or too rich, let me introduce you to the Japanese whipped cream sandwich. 

I saw @testcook post about the whipped cream sandwich he got from 7/11 in Japan and I was intrigued. 

I knew about the fruit and whipped cream sandwich, but never saw one with JUST whipped cream. Our Japanese nanny said she always wished someone would make it with only the cream…and it turns out someone finally did. So I made her dream come true by making her one. 

I sweetened the cream with condensed milk (you can use my mango royale cream recipe) and hand whipped for more density and stability. I love light desserts, and this fits the bill perfectly. The bread has to be right though, good soft fluffy shokupan. Perfection!

📣 “Curry paste” is bad branding.
This is because it makes people think to only use it to make curries. But I suggest thinking of it as “flavour paste”, or a mix of herbs and spices, and use it wherever herbs and spices can be used. 

I made a fish stir fry with red curry paste (cod I think, but it was mystery fish found in freezer 😂). One trick for stir frying with fish is to toss it in any kind of starch/flour and fry them first. Restaurants typically deep fry, but pan frying works just fine. 

This does two important things. One, the coating holds the fish together, preventing it from falling apart when you toss. Two, the coating, creates a surface for the sauce to hold onto so the fish pieces will be more flavourful. 

If you throw raw fish straight into a stir fry, which you certainly can do, you have to be careful not to break it up into bits. If the fish can be safely eaten undercooked, cooking it to medium doneness will also prevent it from falling apart, because fish becomes flaky when it’s well done. 

Finally, I don’t recommend using orange bell pepper for a red curry paste stir fry because everything turns orange and the fish disappears 🤣.

Visited friends over on Vancouver Island this weekend and one of the most charming things about this place is what I call “road eggs”. 

People who own chickens will put out eggs, and sometimes home grown produce, in a little stall, and anyone can just come by and grab them and put money in locked box. There is no one watching. There is no system to prevent theft or underpaying. It’s just a system that works because everyone (or at least enough people) is honest. Note: the money box is locked. 

It’s nice to see there are places in the world where this works.

You can cook a whole meal in a bag! #AD I found this to be such a convenient way to meal prep cuz you basically cook right in the meal’s own storage container. I cook my son’s lunches once and keep it for the whole week, so this was an appealing idea to me. 

Ziploc Endurables is a silicone pouch that is heat resistant up to 425°F, which means you can steam, bake, and microwave in it, and then it can go straight into the fridge or freezer.

This recipe was developed by Chef @susurlee and I love the idea of throwing everything into one pouch, et voila. You can apply the same idea using any other sauces. If you’ve got a stir fry sauce that you like, such as my cashew chicken sauce, that would work here. 

Recipe below, modified slightly from Chef Lee’s original version:

1 large chicken breast (8 oz), butterflied
2 green onions, sliced (or 1 large one)
1 tsp minced ginger
1 red chili, sliced (optional)
Jasmine rice for serving
 
Sauce:
1 Tbsp soy sauce
1 Tbsp oyster sauce
1 Tbsp water
½ tsp brown sugar
1 tsp sesame oil
1 ½ tsp cornstarch
 ¼ tsp black pepper
 
Place chicken, green onions, ginger and chili into a medium Ziploc Endurables. Combine all the sauce ingredients together and whisk until the cornstarch is dissolved and pour into the container. Partially close the pouch and steam for 15-18 minutes. Use tongs to remove from the steamer. Serve with jasmine rice.

You may have seen my recent YouTube video reviewing various instant pad thai products, and most of them were not great. 

So when I saw Mama, a classic Thai brand of instant noodles that usually does a very good job at translating flavours of dishes into instant noodles. I had to give it a try.

First of all, I have to note that this is not a product that exists in Thailand. I have only ever seen this in Canada and the US. Needless to say, Thai people would not settle for the stuff 😂. While many other dishes translate wonderfully into instant noodles (tom yum for example), pad thai is not one of them. But I guess because it is such a popular dish in the West, Mama felt the need to have something available. 

In terms of nailing the flavour of pad thai, this is probably the best of all the ones I tried in my video. Not too sweet, and I would say it is quite recognizable as having pad thai flavor. But the noodle texture is too soft, and overall it still just wasn’t satisfying.

I had to add eggs because after a couple of bites, I just couldn’t keep going without adding something else in there. And I think that speaks to one of the main reasons why I don’t think any of these instant pad thai products are any good. 

👩🏻‍🏫 A good pad thai is SO much more than the noodles. It is all about the combination of the noodles, the eggs, the bean sprouts, the garlic chives, the dried shrimp, etc. etc. In my pad thai recipe you will notice that the noodles make up a surprisingly small proportion of the entire dish. There is so much “stuff” mixed into it. There should be tons of bits within the noodles. 

So when you try to reduce the dish down into just noodles and sauce, it doesn’t matter how well you nail the flavor, it’s always going to feel lacking. Even me adding the eggs here barely helped.

In short, there are dishes that can be turned into instant products well, but pad thai is not one of them.

EACH of these giant prawns was 1000 baht ($27 USD). The biggest I’ve ever had. It took a road trip to get there, and it was worth it. 

Famous giant river prawns from Guimong in Supanburi. So fresh the flesh was sweet and bouncy. Literally oozing with tomalley. Simply seasoned with salt so you can taste the prawns in all its glory.

It’s expensive even by Western standards so imagine that in Thai money 😓. But I had river prawns at a few different places this trip and this was by far the best one. BTW this was the only $$$ thing on the menu. It’s not a fancy place and everything else was cheap and totally delicious. So 80% of the total bill was the cost of the prawns 😂.

Other dishes we had: Tom yum with local fish (ปลาม้า). Napa cabbage stir fried with the prawn’s claw meat. Fried frogs with garlic. Fried clown featherback fish with garlic. Pad gaprao with local fish. Water spinach stir fry. 

Thanks to @b_anc.dr for the recommendation and the road trip.

Friend: Do Thai people celebrate Mid Autumn Festival?

Me: If by “celebrate” you mean eat mooncakes. Yes. 

I grew up eating mooncakes 🥮, but I had zero idea that they were related to the mid autumn festival. In my family, and for many Thai people, we talk about it as the “mooncake festival” and I always thought it was just the time you ate mooncakes more than other times of the year, for reasons that I never asked about. 😂 

Also, you can buy moon cakes year round in Thailand, though they are much more available during the season. 

Fun fact: Moon cakes in Thailand have fillings that are unique to us, and my fave is the pictured: durian paste with 2 salted egg yolks. ✌️

 Usually, I try to share the "traditional" version of a Thai dish, but this was one that I truly felt could benefit from a little hybrid. 

These are my Thai shrimp-cake-fish-cake hybrid. Thai shrimp cakes a crunchy, bouncy and beautiful, but they're pretty plainly seasoned and served with plum sauce. 

Thai fish cakes are some of Thailand's least pretty foods, they're not crunchy, can be chewy if not done well. But they are super tasty cuz they're LOADED with spicy red curry flavour and served with sweet chili sauce.

So I made shrimp cakes that are flavoured like the fish cakes! So I get the crunch, the pretty, AND the flavour.

This special soy sauce is so important to my grandma that she BRINGS it to our house whenever she comes. Cuz our soy sauce is not good enough for her 😂.

This soy sauce I’ve never seen anywhere else. She brings it from her home town  as we can’t get it here in Bangkok. She brings it to specifically make a soy chicken dish “gai kem”. The recipe is on my website as “grandma’s twice cooked chicken”. 

If you asked her she’d say other soy sauces is fine also, but for her taste, it’s gotta be this one. 

I’ve seen this soy sauce all my life and I finally gave it a taste straight up. And it’s…salty 😂. I mean honestly it’s nothing special though it does taste distinctly different from Healthy Boy which is what I use. It tastes closer to Chinese soy sauce, actually. 

Is there a specific brand of ingredient you/your parents/grandparents insist on using because other brands just won’t do?

My last video was on one of the most important sauces in Thai cuisine, nam jim jeaw (link in bio). But there is another sauce that's equally important!

🦐 If you've ever had seafood in Thailand, you were definitely also served a small bowl of spicy, tart sauce. This is "nam jim seafood," literally "seafood dipping sauce." For Thai people, it is the absolute best condiment for seafood, and we will not settle for anything else! The sauce can be orange or green, depending on the colour of the chilies used. 

I know I'm not the only Thai who's brought my own nam jim seafood to seafood restaurants outside of Thailand 😆.

You know what I noticed in recent years whenever I go to Thailand? If you order “chicken wings” in a restaurant, most of the time you will get only flats. No drumettes. This year I finally wondered…. WHERE DO ALL THE DRUMETTES GO?? 

Then as I was working on my last recipe (link in bio) KFC Wingz Zabb, it occurred to me that KFC uses *only* drumettes. 😮

So the natural jump to conclusion is that KFC buys up all the drumettes for their Wingz Zabb and so other restaurants only have flats left?!!? Could that actually be it? 

Anyway I had a bunch of wing flats leftover after I filmed Wingz Zabb. So the only natural thing to make is fish sauce wings. 3 ingredients, no joke. (Recipe on the website). 

Wings, fish sauce, and rice flour. Pepper is optional. You can shallow fry these cuz they’re flat so no deep frying needed. But do use a splatter guard. So simple and so good.

I also made a cucumber tuna salad which has tuna, kewpie mayo, lao gan ma chili oil, and obviously 🥒 . Very good for only 4 ingredients!

Sometimes things go wrong in the kitchen but it works out anyway. 

My in laws gave me a frozen block of imitation crab (they like to give us random groceries because they shop at Costco and always have too much of everything. But I digress.) I happened to have some homemade red curry paste that needed to be used so I thought I’d make a red curry with imitation crab. 

I put the frozen block of crab in the curry sauce, closed the lid and walked away, thinking I’d come back and it’ll be all thawed. 

What I did not know was that there is enough starch in imitation crab to make it behave more like starch than protein. And starches, unlike protein, can absorb liquid. I came back and not only did it thaw, it sucked up ALL the liquid in the pot 🤣.

So the next natural move is to pretend I was making a stir fry. Added spinach and called it a day. It was great, lol.

What better way to celebrate American Thanksgiving than to make American fried rice! 🇺🇸 🇹🇭 

OK joking aside, American fried rice is an actual Thai dish, and I have a recipe for it linked in my bio. The story is that the dish was created using leftovers from an American breakfast buffet for American soldiers who were in Thailand during the Vietnam war (I have no idea if this is true btw). 

So ingredients used are all Western, including ketchup, which is the main seasoning for the rice, fried chicken, hot dogs (which we consider as sausages), sunny side up eggs, carrots, peas, onion, raisins, and sometimes ham.

Kids love this dish, and so when my brother @artchongart came to visit I decided to make it for the nostalgia. As an adult I also put some prik nam pla on it. So very satisfying 🤤

And it is not complete if the hotdogs are not octopus shaped 🐙.

Would you buy these?

I went to a mom and pop Asian store and saw these green papayas, partially peeled, for sale for cheap. My assumption is that there was something wrong on the skin, maybe bruises, or even mold. But instead of throwing them away, they removed the bad parts and then sell them for cheap.

I love this idea of selling less than perfect produce for cheaper, maybe not done in exactly this way, but in some manner. It’s just the idea of it I’m thinking of. Because at most other stores, these would be in the trash. But if YOU had a green papaya at home, and the skin had a little bit of mould on it, you would probably just cut it off and use the good part. You probably wouldn’t throw the whole thing away. 

With grocery prices rising, I’m sure many people would be more than happy to have this as an option. 

PS. For food safety police out there, I know having cut produce out unrefrigerated is not cool, but that’s beside the point 😅.

NEW VIDEO: This is the classic Thai dish I make the most often today, by a long shot.

This soul soothing soup is near and dear to my heart because I grew up eating some variation of it pretty much weekly. 

It's called "gaeng jued" which literally means "bland curry"...but it is anything but bland! It's so named to contrast it against other spicy curries in Thai cuisine, because this is one of the few soups we eat that is not spicy at all. This is why it's so popular in families with kids.

And now that I have a kid, this has become the most frequent menu in my house because he loves it, as do I. And because it is such a modifiable soup, I can change up the meat, vegetables, and all the other stuff in it so it's not the same thing each time.

In this video, it's gaeng jued 101. It's not a recipe but the principle of how to make any kind of gaeng jued using ingredients you have and/or like.

Growing up in Thailand we did not celebrate Christmas and we didn’t even have any event that my family celebrated to this degree. Definitely not all this gift giving. 

Then I came to Canada as a childless adult, Christmas was just like…a nice time when the city is decorated, and most years I went back to Thailand during Christmas. 

Then I started dating my husband and Christmas started to involve his family and some low key gift giving. 

Then I had a child and suddenly Christmas became OMG THE BIGGEST THING!!! PRESENTSSSS!!! ACTIVITIEEESSSS! COOKIESSSS!! SOOOO EXCITING!!! And we went from having no Christmas tree and didn’t care for one to a fully decorated home, gingerbread making, and a million gifts in a blink of an eye. 

Christmas with kids is so much more magical, more fun, and more exhausting. And quite honestly as a Thai I’m still getting used to this intensity. It’s like I’m experiencing culture shock round 2 😂 

Hope you all are having a great time with loved ones!
